postcontent: STILL HAVE AMMO----SOLD RIFLEOLD Russian Mosin Nagant M91/30 manufactured in 1939, matching SNs, overall good condition, some scuffs on the stock, mechanically excellent with a clean Bore with well defined  lands and grooves. I just had the gun smith check it out with a bore scope. Thel lands and grooves are in pristine contition.  About 91/30s: nearly all were counter bored to maintain field accuracy despite battlefield conditions.  The projectile does not touch the barrel the last inch or so where the rifling was bored out to about 7.80 mm.  So you could actually drill holes there for a ported barrel.  If you know firearms then you know you can inspect  the rifling by removing the bolt and peering through the breach end towards light. The counter bore as well as the rifling is readily verifiable even by simple field inspection. Before counter boring, these rifles had severe bore and button damage from battle field abuse that drastically reduced accuracy.  Counter boring was the simple and effective solution.This rifle is vVery accurate: I consistently hit hand sized 6 shot groups at 110 meters without wearing my glasses with stock iron sights. Portuguese Armalite Ar10 in decent shape. It is a serial number 007XXX with the Porto reinforced lower.
First let's talk about the good. The rifle will be sold with two original magazines, has a potentially hand made wood grip. The entire rifle was painted and the paint on the grip is coming off pretty rapidly, which is good. I haven't used any chemicals on it yet, figured the next owner might want the hobby of cleaning it up. The rifle is tight for it's age. There is some movement between the upper and the lower but not much. It does fire and cycle like a new gun. No issues whatsoever. You are buying a pre ban weapon that actually works.
Now the not so good. As mentioned it was painted, it wasn't what I'd consider a professional job. If it's going to be a show piece then it could use a refinish. It is missing the original buttstock and handguard. For the handguard it has a modern tactical rail (original front sight though). The buttstock pad came with it however it fits poorly/almost not at all. The buffer tube (original) is larger in diameter than modern buffer tubes so finding a buttstock isn't easy. I'm including the buttstock pad that came with it and you're welcome to modify it to fit better or source original parts.
The rifle shows that it was in battle in some spots. Has marks but is an awesome weapon. Has Armalite markings on the barrel and BCG so overall a lot of original parts are there.
Looking for a buyer who knows what it is and I'm willing to meet within reason for local buyers.
I will entertain trades plus cash.
I will ship at buyer's expense to an FFL ONLY.

The Redding Competition Bushing Neck Sizer Die Set includes a Competition Bushing Neck Sizing Die, Body Die and Competition Seating Die. Both the Bushing Neck Sizing Die and the Competition Seating Die feature micrometer adjustments for precision. Bushings and Shellholder sold separately.
Competition Bushing Sizing Die -- With this die, the cartridge case is completely supported and aligned with the sizing bushing before the sizing process begins. As the sizing process starts, the cartridge case remains supported in the tightly chambered sliding sleeve as it moves upward while the resizing bushing self centers on the case neck. The decapping rod is maintained in precise alignment by using the internal parts of the die as a linear support much like a firing pin. While the micrometer adjustment of the bushing position delivers precise control to the desired amount of the neck length to be sized. (Bushings are sold separately)
The Body Die -- is designed to full length resize the case body only and bump the shoulder position for proper chambering without disturbing the case neck. It is intended for use only to resize cases which have become increasingly difficult to chamber after repeated firing and neck sizing.
Competition Seating Die -- The bullet guide to seating stem fit is so precise that the seating stem can actually be demonstrated to float on a column of air. The micrometer is calibrated in .001" increments. It also has a zero set feature that allows you to zero the micrometer to your rifle or favorite seating depth.

title: For Trade:  LNIB Taurus Millennium G2 9mm (Subcompact)
postcontent:
Great for conceal carry a Subcompact Taurus Millennium G2 in 9mm. It comes with factory case, and 2 - 12 round mags. The pistol is in like new condition.
Specifications: Taurus Millenium G2

Model: 111G2
Finish: Blue
Caliber: 9 mm (.40 coming soon!)
Capacity: 12+1
Weight: 22 oz
Barrel Length: 3.2 inches
Length: 6.24 inches


Fit and Finish * * * * *
The level of quality evident in the G2 is in line with $600 – $900 polymer pistols. No rattles, squeaks, or clumsy machining.

Reliability * * * * *
Zero FTF/FTEs during testing, but due to current ammo shortages, this wasn’t really a complete test.

Accuracy * * * *
For a carry gun, it was accurate enough. This is definitely not a 50 yard pistol, but can definitely be considered combat accurate.

Carry * * * *
From a form perspective, this is a very concealable gun capable of holding a decent amount of 9 mm. However, it has a manual safety that’s hard to (de)actuate in a hurry.

Trigger * * * * *
Crisp and breaks like glass at 6 lbs. exactly. The reset point is a short throw away, and has an audible click. The second strike capability is nice, but in my opinion doesn’t add a lot of value.

Cleaning * * * * *
Super easy.

Overall * * * *
As a standalone product, this is an awesome gun. I was thoroughly impressed and I would have expected something like this to cost $500-$600. For a $349 price tag, this may be the best “bang for the buck” pistol I have had the opportunity to test.

Sig 556R.  Good condition.  2nd generation with Steel Magazine shelf.  The long handguard style is no longer in production. The new XI line have reported issues. The 556R is basically an AK47 with improved ergos. Round count ~200. 

Includes:  Sig Diopter sights, Hogue Grip, 2 detachable foregrip rails, 1 Tapco Slabside Magazine. 

 It has been sitting in the corner of my safe for months. Decided I should make space for something else.

Sig Sauer description:
SIG556 Russian, chambered for the widely used 7.62 x 39mm caliber. Using AK-type magazines, the shooter now has a more potent round for small to medium game. The SIG556R features a Swiss folding stock, and an M1913 rail for accessory attachment. The 16” barrel features four-groove rifling and a twist rate of 1:9.5”. The SIG556R measures 35.875” but can fold to 26”, making it ideal for situations where maximum maneuverability is required. For Special Forces requiring an accurate, more potent rifle, chambered in 7.62x39mm, the SIG556R sets a new standard for dependable
operation and function.

Meet at West Coast Armory Bellevue or Pantel Tactical for transfer.
